{
  "In a river meander, erosion occurs primarily on which bank?": "",
  "Both banks erode equally": "",
  "Only the river bottom, not the banks": "",
  "The inner bank where water flows slowly": "",
  "The outer bank where water flows fastest": "",
  "Water travels fastest along the outer curve of a meander due to centrifugal force, which concentrates erosion on the outer bank while slower water on the inner bank deposits sediment.": "",
  "How does an oxbow lake form?": "",
  "A dam is built across a river channel": "",
  "A glacier melts and fills a depression": "",
  "Heavy rainfall fills a dry river valley": "",
  "A meander loop is cut off from the main channel when erosion breaks through the narrow neck": "",
  "Continued erosion on the outer banks of a tight meander eventually cuts through the narrow neck of land between the loops, creating a straighter channel and isolating the old curve as a crescent-shaped oxbow lake.": "",
  "V-shaped valleys are characteristic of which part of a river?": "",
  "The wide floodplain": "",
  "The delta region": "",
  "The upper course where the gradient is steep": "",
  "The lower course near the river mouth": "",
  "In the upper course, rapid downward erosion by fast-flowing water cuts a narrow V-shaped valley with steep sides, as the river focuses most of its energy on cutting deeper rather than wider.": "",
  "Why are floodplains considered fertile agricultural land?": "",
  "They contain volcanic soil from nearby eruptions": "",
  "Periodic flooding deposits nutrient-rich sediment across the flat land": "",
  "Underground limestone releases minerals into the soil": "",
  "Farmers add extra fertilizer to compensate for poor soil": "",
  "When rivers overflow their banks during floods, they deposit fine, nutrient-rich sediment called alluvium across the floodplain, creating exceptionally fertile soil that has supported agriculture for thousands of years.": "",
  "What features would you expect to find in the lower course of a river?": "",
  "Wide floodplains, meanders, and deltas": "",
  "V-shaped valleys and steep gorges": "",
  "Waterfalls and rapids": "",
  "Glacial features like cirques and aretes": "",
  "The lower course has a gentle gradient, so the river flows slowly and focuses on lateral erosion, creating wide meandering curves, broad floodplains, and depositional features like deltas at the river mouth.": "",
  "What does the Continental Divide in North America determine?": "",
  "Whether water flows toward the Atlantic/Gulf of Mexico or toward the Pacific Ocean": "",
  "Where rainfall is heaviest versus lightest": "",
  "Where earthquakes are most likely to occur": "",
  "The boundary between igneous and sedimentary rock": "",
  "The Continental Divide runs along the crest of the Rocky Mountains and separates watersheds that drain into the Pacific Ocean on the west from those that drain into the Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico on the east.": "",
  "What creates rapids and waterfalls in a river?": "",
  "Bands of resistant rock that erode more slowly than surrounding softer rock": "",
  "Deposition of sediment creating underwater barriers": "",
  "Flat terrain that allows the river to spread wide": "",
  "Wind pushing against the river flow": "",
  "When a river flows over alternating bands of hard and soft rock, the soft rock erodes faster, creating a step or drop where the resistant rock remains, forming rapids and waterfalls through differential erosion.": "",
  "How are natural levees built up along a river?": "",
  "By wind blowing sand into ridges along the riverbank": "",
  "By glaciers pushing debris along the river channel": "",
  "By repeated flooding that deposits coarser sediment along the river banks, building raised ridges": "",
  "By humans stacking sandbags during floods": "",
  "During floods, the coarsest sediment drops out immediately at the river's edge as floodwater spills over the banks and suddenly slows, gradually building up natural raised ridges called levees on both sides.": "",
  "What happens to a river's sediment-carrying capacity when its velocity increases?": "",
  "It decreases because the water flows past sediment too quickly to pick it up": "",
  "It stays the same regardless of speed": "",
  "It decreases because faster water is less dense": "",
  "It increases, allowing the river to carry larger and more numerous particles": "",
  "Faster-flowing water has more kinetic energy and turbulence, which allows it to pick up, suspend, and carry larger and heavier sediment particles than slower water can transport.": "",
  "What type of valley is carved by a glacier rather than a river?": "",
  "A deep canyon with vertical walls": "",
  "A narrow V-shaped valley": "",
  "A wide U-shaped valley": "",
  "A flat-bottomed rift valley": "",
  "Glaciers carve wide, flat-bottomed U-shaped valleys because their massive width grinds away both the valley floor and sides, unlike rivers that primarily erode downward to create narrow V-shaped valleys.": "",
  "What is a watershed?": "",
  "A type of waterfall found in mountain regions": "",
  "The deepest point in a river channel": "",
  "The total land area that drains into a particular river system": "",
  "A building used to store water for distribution": "",
  "A watershed, also called a drainage basin, includes all the land where precipitation flows downhill into a particular river and its tributaries, bounded by ridges and divides that separate it from adjacent watersheds.": "",
  "What is a meander?": "",
  "A wide, looping curve in a river formed by erosion on the outer bank and deposition on the inner bank": "",
  "A waterfall where a river drops over a cliff": "",
  "A human-made dam across a river channel": "",
  "A straight, fast-flowing section of a river": "",
  "A meander is a sinuous bend in a river channel that forms as water erodes the outer bank of a curve and deposits sediment on the inner bank, causing the river to migrate laterally across its floodplain.": "",
  "What is a floodplain?": "",
  "A mountain plateau above the tree line": "",
  "The flat area alongside a river that is periodically flooded and covered with nutrient-rich sediment": "",
  "An area that is permanently underwater": "",
  "A desert plain that never receives rain": "",
  "A floodplain is the relatively flat land bordering a river that is subject to periodic flooding, receiving deposits of fine, nutrient-rich alluvial sediment each time the river overtops its banks.": "",
  "What is a point bar?": "",
  "A deep pool at the base of a waterfall": "",
  "A gentle slope of deposited sediment on the inner bank of a meander where water flows slowly": "",
  "A dam-like structure that blocks river flow": "",
  "A rocky cliff on the outer bank of a river meander": "",
  "A point bar is a depositional feature that forms on the inner bank of a meander where water velocity is lowest, causing sediment to accumulate in a gently sloping deposit of sand and gravel.": "",
  "What is a tributary?": "",
  "The point where a river enters the ocean": "",
  "A man-made channel that diverts river water": "",
  "The main stem of a river system": "",
  "A smaller stream or river that flows into a larger one": "",
  "A tributary is any stream or river that feeds into a larger river rather than flowing directly into the ocean, contributing water and sediment to the main channel and increasing its discharge downstream.": "",
  "What does 'river discharge' mean?": "",
  "The speed at which a river flows downstream": "",
  "The total length of a river from source to mouth": "",
  "The temperature of the river water": "",
  "The volume of water flowing past a point per unit time, measured in cubic meters or feet per second": "",
  "River discharge is the volume of water passing a specific point in a given amount of time, calculated by multiplying the cross-sectional area of the channel by the average water velocity.": "",
  "What is a river's base level?": "",
  "The widest point in the river's channel": "",
  "The point where a river originates in the mountains": "",
  "The deepest pool in the entire river system": "",
  "The lowest level to which a river can erode, usually sea level for the main channel": "",
  "Base level is the lowest elevation to which a river can erode its channel, with ultimate base level being sea level for rivers flowing to the ocean, though lakes and resistant rock can create local base levels.": "",
  "What does 'gradient' mean when describing a river?": "",
  "The slope or steepness of the river channel, measured as the drop in elevation over a given distance": "",
  "The volume of sediment carried by the river": "",
  "The width of the river channel from bank to bank": "",
  "The temperature change along the river's length": "",
  "A river's gradient is the steepness of its channel, expressed as the change in elevation per unit of horizontal distance, and it directly influences water velocity, erosion power, and the types of landforms created.": "",
  "What is a drainage divide?": "",
  "The point where a river divides around an island": "",
  "A ridge of high land that separates two adjacent watersheds, directing water flow in opposite directions": "",
  "A man-made canal that splits a river into two channels": "",
  "The boundary between freshwater and saltwater in an estuary": "",
  "A drainage divide is an elevated boundary, typically a ridge or mountain crest, that separates adjacent drainage basins so that precipitation falling on one side flows into one river system and precipitation on the other side flows into a different system.": "",
  "What does 'stream piracy' mean?": "",
  "When one stream captures the headwaters of another stream through erosion, diverting its flow": "",
  "When humans divert a river's water for irrigation": "",
  "When underground water steals flow from a surface river": "",
  "When a river floods and temporarily changes course": "",
  "Stream piracy, also called stream capture, occurs when the headward erosion of one stream breaches the drainage divide and captures the water of an adjacent stream, redirecting its flow into the capturing stream's drainage basin.": "",
  "A city planner is reviewing a proposal to build a new housing development on a wide, flat area directly alongside a winding river. Historical records show the river has flooded this area three times in the past century. Why should the planner be concerned about approving this development?": "",
  "The meanders indicate the river is drying up and will not provide water to residents": "",
  "The flat terrain means the area will experience frequent earthquakes": "",
  "The area is a natural floodplain that the river periodically inundates, putting homes at risk of flood damage": "",
  "The winding river will erode the development from below through underground channels": "",
  "The flat area alongside a winding river is its natural floodplain, which is designed by nature to absorb overflow during high-water events, and building there puts property at significant risk of flooding damage.": "",
  "A kayaker notices that as she paddles around a sharp bend in a river, the water on the outside of the curve is deep and fast-moving, while the inside of the curve has a shallow, sandy beach. Over many years, what will happen to this meander?": "",
  "The meander will grow more exaggerated as the outer bank erodes and the inner bank builds up with sediment": "",
  "The curve will straighten out as the outer bank fills with sediment": "",
  "Both banks will erode equally, widening the river without changing the curve": "",
  "The river will reverse direction and flow the opposite way": "",
  "Continued erosion on the faster-flowing outer bank and deposition on the slower inner bank causes the meander to become more pronounced over time, eventually potentially cutting off to form an oxbow lake.": "",
  "A farmer in Egypt relies on annual Nile River floods to fertilize his crops. After the Aswan High Dam was built upstream in the 1960s, the floods stopped reaching his land. What consequence is the farmer most likely experiencing?": "",
  "His crops are growing better because the floods no longer damage them": "",
  "His soil is becoming less fertile because the annual deposit of nutrient-rich sediment from flooding has ceased": "",
  "The river has completely dried up below the dam": "",
  "His fields are now too wet because the dam releases extra water": "",
  "The Aswan Dam traps sediment in Lake Nasser, preventing the nutrient-rich silt from reaching downstream floodplains during annual floods, forcing farmers to rely on artificial fertilizers to maintain soil productivity.": "",
  "Geologists studying aerial photographs notice that a river in the Great Plains has wide, sweeping meanders and a very flat surrounding landscape, while a river in the Rocky Mountains cuts through a narrow, deep gorge with no meanders. What explains these differences?": "",
  "Different rock types cause the rivers to behave differently regardless of slope": "",
  "The Great Plains river is older than the mountain river": "",
  "The gentle gradient of the plains allows lateral erosion and meandering, while the steep mountain gradient causes rapid downward erosion creating a narrow valley": "",
  "The mountain river has more water than the plains river": "",
  "River gradient determines erosion patterns: the steep Rocky Mountain gradient concentrates energy on downward cutting, creating gorges, while the gentle Plains gradient shifts energy toward lateral erosion, producing wide meanders and floodplains.": "",
  "A community downstream of a new housing development notices their stream, which used to run clear, is now muddy after every rain event, and the channel is filling with sediment. The development removed trees and paved large areas. What chain of events caused this problem?": "",
  "Removing vegetation and adding pavement increased runoff speed and volume, causing more erosion of exposed soil and increased sediment delivery to the stream": "",
  "The new houses are pumping muddy water directly into the stream": "",
  "The development changed the mineral composition of nearby rocks": "",
  "Underground pipes from the development are injecting sediment into the stream": "",
  "Clearing vegetation removes root stabilization, and impervious surfaces like pavement prevent infiltration, increasing surface runoff volume and velocity, which erodes exposed soil and delivers excessive sediment to receiving streams.": "",
  "A park ranger notices that a river in Yellowstone has undercut a tall bank of volcanic ash, creating an overhang. Heavy rain is forecast for the weekend. What is the most likely near-term consequence for this riverbank?": "",
  "The volcanic ash will absorb the rain and become harder": "",
  "The rain will cause the river to reverse direction": "",
  "The overhang will likely collapse into the river as the rain saturates and weakens the unsupported material": "",
  "The rain will cement the ash into solid rock": "",
  "The undercut bank creates an overhang that becomes increasingly unstable as the unsupported weight of material grows, and heavy rain will saturate the ash, adding weight and reducing cohesion, making collapse into the river very likely.": "",
  "An environmental scientist is comparing two watersheds of similar size. Watershed A is 90% forested, while Watershed B is 60% agricultural farmland with bare fields in winter. After identical rainstorms, which watershed will produce more sediment in its streams, and why?": "",
  "Watershed B, because bare agricultural soil lacks root protection and canopy cover, allowing rain to erode soil more easily": "",
  "Watershed A, because tree roots loosen the soil and push it into streams": "",
  "Both produce equal sediment since the rainstorms were identical": "",
  "Watershed A, because forests produce more leaf litter that washes into streams": "",
  "Forested watersheds produce far less sediment because tree canopy intercepts rain, leaf litter protects the soil surface, and extensive root networks bind the soil, while bare agricultural fields are highly vulnerable to rain splash erosion and runoff.": "",
  "A family living beside a river notices that every spring, their backyard seems to get a little smaller as the river edge creeps closer to their house. They live on the outside of a river bend. What is happening and what should they expect in the future?": "",
  "The outer bank of the meander is being eroded by fast-flowing water, and their property will continue to lose land as the meander migrates": "",
  "Underground springs are dissolving the soil beneath their yard": "",
  "The river is rising permanently due to increased rainfall": "",
  "Sediment is being deposited on their bank, pushing the river closer": "",
  "Properties on the outer bank of a river meander are subject to ongoing lateral erosion because the fastest-flowing water concentrates against the outer bank, progressively undercutting and removing material year after year.": "",
  "During a field trip, students observe that a river has built up its banks higher than the surrounding floodplain, so the river actually flows above the level of the nearby land. The teacher explains this is common in the lower Mississippi. How did this situation develop?": "",
  "Engineers artificially raised the riverbed with fill material": "",
  "Repeated floods deposited coarse sediment along the banks, building natural levees that raised the channel above the floodplain": "",
  "Tectonic forces lifted the riverbed above the surrounding plain": "",
  "The river dug down so deeply that it appears to be elevated": "",
  "Over centuries of repeated flooding, the coarsest sediment is deposited right at the river's edge each time it overtops its banks, gradually building up natural levees that can raise the channel above the surrounding floodplain.": "",
  "A town's water supply comes from a reservoir fed by a river. After a logging company clearcuts the forest upstream in the watershed, the town notices their reservoir is filling with sediment much faster than expected, and the water is murkier. An engineer warns that at this rate, the reservoir's useful life will be cut in half. What explains this accelerated sedimentation?": "",
  "Removing the forest exposed soil to erosion by rain and runoff, dramatically increasing sediment delivery to the river and reservoir": "",
  "Tree stumps decomposing in the forest released mud into the water": "",
  "The logging changed the river's flow direction toward the reservoir": "",
  "The logging equipment directly pushed soil into the river": "",
  "Clearcutting removes the vegetation that protects soil from erosion, causing massive increases in sediment entering streams from rain splash, sheet erosion, and gully formation on the now-bare slopes, which then accumulates in the downstream reservoir.": ""
}